{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":4369,"record_hash":"sha256:199da1dbbef55fb2cd159ae959e94a5a836df059d0a534c9816facfde658080f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:42:35.833Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:145-146) [added]\n[P1] Path whitelist lets base64 secrets through\n\n`/` is part of the candidate alphabet, but `is_pathish()` treats any candidate starting with `/` or containing at least two slashes as safe. That means normal base64-looking credentials with slashes can exceed the entropy threshold and still remain unredacted. I would remove or heavily tighten this whitelist; over-redacting a path in `source_record` is less risky than missing opaque secrets.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:116-118) [added]\n[P2] Hex secrets are effectively exempt\n\nPure hex strings cannot exceed 4 bits of entropy per character, so the `> 4.0` threshold will not catch them; then 40- and 64-character hex strings are explicitly treated as common hashes. That preserves commit/SHA-looking values, but it also lets common hex-encoded credentials or HMAC keys pass unchanged.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nlets take care of these\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:42:35.833Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:145-146) [added]\n[P1] Path whitelist lets base64 secrets through\n\n`/` is part of the candidate alphabet, but `is_pathish()` treats any candidate starting with `/` or containing at least two slashes as safe. That means normal base64-looking credentials with slashes can exceed the entropy threshold and still remain unredacted. I would remove or heavily tighten this whitelist; over-redacting a path in `source_record` is less risky than missing opaque secrets.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:116-118) [added]\n[P2] Hex secrets are effectively exempt\n\nPure hex strings cannot exceed 4 bits of entropy per character, so the `> 4.0` threshold will not catch them; then 40- and 64-character hex strings are explicitly treated as common hashes. That preserves commit/SHA-looking values, but it also lets common hex-encoded credentials or HMAC keys pass unchanged.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nlets take care of these\n"}]}}}